    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>SOLOMONS &#38; CHAPMAN&#44;<lb/>
            Agts.&#44; Lawrence&#39;s &#34;Pure Linen&#34; Papers&#44; &#38;c.&#44;<lb/>
            SUCCESSORS TO PHILP &#38; SOLOMONS&#44;<lb/>
            METROPOLITAN BOOKSTORE&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Washington&#44; Nov. 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1877.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and Esteemed friend.<lb/></p>
            <p>Many<lb/> thanks for the copy of<lb/> your sermon sent me&#44;<lb/> which I have read<lb/> with much pleasure<lb/> and profit.  I need<lb/> hardly say I agree<lb/> with every word you<lb/> uttered&#44; and sincerely<lb/> wish every person<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>in the land were<lb/> made familiar with<lb/> its valued teachings.<lb/></p>
            <p>The telegram just<lb/> received from Ida<lb/> has compelled me<lb/> to advise her to leave<lb/> your hospitable dwell&#45;<lb/>ing to&#45;day to perform<lb/> a sad act of duty&#44;<lb/> and my regrets min&#45;<lb/>gle with hers that&#44;<lb/> she will be deprived<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>the pleasure of your company and<lb/> that of your dear family&#44; which<lb/> she had so hopefully looked<lb/> forward to&#44;&#45;&#45;but &#34;men proposes<lb/> and God disposes.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>Accept my thanks for your<lb/> politeness and kindness to Ida<lb/> and I trust some day to<lb/> have it in my power to re&#45;<lb/>ciprocate it&#44; at least in part.<lb/></p>
            <p>Ida spoke of the intention of<lb/> your daughter to read an essay before<lb/> the &#34;Y. M. H. A.&#34; on Tuesday next.<lb/>  If it is published&#44; may I trouble<lb/> you for a copy&#63;  With regards<lb/> to you all&#44; in which my family most<lb/> heartily join&#44; I am&#44; with considerations<lb/></p>
            
            <p>of regard	Yours Very Truly	A. S. Solomons<lb/>
            Rev. S. Morais<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
